<HL>
   Business Brief -- Drexel Burnham Lambert Group:
   Government Securities Unit
   Also Files Under Chapter 11
</HL>
<DATE>
06/22/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   FLFE J.NOM
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   A Drexel Burnham Lambert Group Inc. unit that specializes
in trading government securities joined the parent company in
bankruptcy-law proceedings.
   Drexel filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the U.S.
Bankruptcy Code Feb. 13; several of its subsidiaries
subsequently filed as well.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In its filing in federal bankruptcy court in Manhattan,
Drexel Burnham Lambert Government Securities Inc. said that
as of March 30, its total assets were $262.2 million and
total liabilities were $155.2 million. The parent company
began liquidating its subsidiaries' assets after it filed its
own Chapter 11 petition.
   The bankruptcy proceedings for the parent company and the
subsidiaries are being combined under Judge Howard Buschman
III in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Manhattan. Drexel has said a
single reorganization plan will be developed for all the
entities.
   In its filing, the government securities unit said its
largest unsecured creditors include Florida Federal Savings &amp;
Loan of St. Petersburg, Fla., which is owed $204,718; Nomura
Securities Co., $103,442; Key Bank of Albany, $47,467; and
Colorado National Bank of Denver, $20,260.
